Ritha is 51 years old, married and has a 20-year-old son. She has a business making and selling plaster handicraft products.

Ritha is enterprising, patient, generous, understanding, responsible and hard-working. She has her business in the rural "El Torno" area where there are businesses specialising in producing meat, vegetables, fruits and other products. There are also wholesale distributors who sell products to the city’s different markets and supermarkets. 

With a tropical and humid climate, the temperature here swings between 18 and 35ºC.

Ritha is dark skinned and short; she has long black wavy hair and speaks Guaraní as her native language. She also speaks Spanish for her business. (In the photo, Ritha is sitting on the right in navy blue shorts). Ritha shares her life with her husband, a driver, and their son who works and studies. The family lives in a house that they own. The house is made of bricks and has running water and electricity.

Ritha’s desire to get ahead have brought her to create a loan group with people with the following types of businesses: restaurant, businesses selling soft-drinks, shirts, baby clothes, crisps, sports clothes, meat, and a corner shop. The group has come together in order to apply for a loan and expand their businesses. 

Ritha herself has a business selling plaster handicraft products. The main products that she needs are moulds (usually made of silicon), plaster, water, mixing bowls and oil. 

Ritha carries out the following steps to make products: 

•	She fills the mould with water to see how much plaster she will need;
•	She moves the water to the bowl and begins, gradually, to add the plaster until the water has been absorbed;
•	She transfers the resulting paste into the oiled-up mould; 
•	Once full, she shakes the mould to get rid of bubbles;
•	Ritha then waits 20-30 minutes before removing the product from the mould.;
•	She then trims of any excess on the edges;
•	She leaves the statues to dry over one or two days; 
•	Finally, she sands the figurines, if necessary, before painting them.

Ritha says, “My work began because of a need to make Christmas figurines: angels, doves, and the three kings. Then I started going to fayres and I made piggy banks. The business moved along these lines and I am still working in it.”

Ritha’s dream is for her daughter to have a profession. Ritha wants to buy work supplies in bulk in order to take advantage of end-of-year sales. This is Ritha’s third loan in five years with the organisation. Ritha works independently.

Ritha is applying for this loan in order to buy plaster materials in bulk in order to increase production.
